    <h1>The Bitcoin <em>Doubling</em> Ladder</h1>
    <p class="dl-subtitle">Bitcoin's price has doubled, on the trend, roughly every 12.8% of the way through its life so far &mdash; a steady cadence it has kept since the genesis block in 2009. That regularity is real. What it means is more interesting, and more honest, than &ldquo;Bitcoin doubles on a clock.&rdquo;</p>
  </header>

  <!-- ATTRIBUTION (prominent, near the top) -->
  <div class="dl-attribution">
    <div class="dl-attribution-label">Lineage &amp; attribution</div>
    <p>This page builds directly on the doubling-cadence framing of <strong>Matthew Mezinskis</strong> (<a href="https://www.porkopolis.io/thechart/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Porkopolis Economics &middot; porkopolis.io/thechart</a>), whose published table first laid the per-doubling progression out as a ladder. The underlying power-law theory it rests on originates with <strong>Dr.&nbsp;Giovanni Santostasi</strong>, and the earliest logarithmic-regression sketch of Bitcoin's price came from the pseudonymous <strong>Trolololo</strong> (<a href="https://bitcointalk.org/index.php?topic=831547.0" target="_blank" rel="noopener">BitcoinTalk, 2014</a>). The reframing, the deviation analysis, and any errors here are this site's own.</p>
  </div>

  <!-- THESIS -->
  <section class="dl-hero">
    <div class="dl-hero-stat">Each price doubling takes a fixed <em>percentage</em> longer in days &mdash; not a fixed number of years.</div>
    <p class="dl-hero-body">In Mezinskis's table, every doubling of the trend takes roughly <strong>12.8% more</strong> days-of-life than the one before. It looks like a hidden metronome. It is not. It is the <em>arithmetic fingerprint of a power law</em> &mdash; and once you see why, the regularity stops being mystical and becomes something you can check against the actual record.</p>
  </section>

  <!-- WHAT IT IS (and isn't) -->
  <section class="dl-section">
    <h2>The fingerprint, not the clock</h2>
    <p>Start from the model this site documents in <a href="/the-power-law.html">The Power Law</a>: the trend price is <em>price = a &middot; day<sup>b</sup></em>, where <em>day</em> is Bitcoin's age in days since the Genesis block (3&nbsp;January&nbsp;2009) and the exponent <em>b</em> is about 5.76.</p>
    <p>Ask how long it takes the trend to double. If <em>a&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;day<sub>2</sub><sup>b</sup>&nbsp;=&nbsp;2&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;a&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;day<sub>1</sub><sup>b</sup></em>, then <em>day<sub>2</sub>&nbsp;&divide;&nbsp;day<sub>1</sub>&nbsp;=&nbsp;2<sup>1/b</sup></em>. With <em>b&nbsp;&asymp;&nbsp;5.76</em>, that ratio is <strong>2<sup>1/5.76</sup>&nbsp;&asymp;&nbsp;1.128</strong>. Every doubling requires the network to get about <strong>12.8% older</strong> &mdash; always the same percentage, forever.</p>
    <div class="dl-insight">
      <p>The ~12.8%-per-doubling cadence isn't bitcoin keeping time. It is what <em>any</em> power law of exponent 5.76 must do, by algebra alone. The regularity is in the math, not in the market.</p>
    </div>
    <p>This matters because it kills a tempting misreading. The ladder does <strong>not</strong> say &ldquo;bitcoin doubles every N years.&rdquo; A fixed 12.8% of a growing age means each doubling takes <em>longer in calendar time</em> than the last: 128 days when the network was 1,000 days old, but 766 days when it was 6,000 days old. The cadence is constant in proportion and stretching in years. Saying otherwise &mdash; treating the rungs as a schedule &mdash; is the single most common way the Power Law gets misused. So we say it plainly: <strong>the ladder is a consequence of the exponent, not a promise about the calendar.</strong></p>
  </section>

  <!-- VISUAL A — THE DOUBLING LADDER -->
